@page "/"

<PageTitle>Enki &mdash; Home</PageTitle>

<h1 class="enki-section-title">Overview</h1>
<p class="enki-section-subtitle">
    AMR survey data platform. Per-tenant isolation on SQL Server; Active +
    Archive database pairs; ASP.NET Identity + OpenIddict authentication.
</p>

<AuthorizeView>
    <Authorized>
        <div class="enki-card enki-bracket-frame" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">
            <div class="enki-kicker">Welcome back</div>
            <h2 style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0.5rem; font-weight: 300;">
                @context.User.Identity?.Name
            </h2>
            <p class="enki-dim" style="margin: 0;">
                Use the sidebar to jump into tenant administration. Drilling
                domain surfaces &mdash; Jobs, Wells, Runs, Gradients, Shots,
                Surveys &mdash; land in Phase&nbsp;6b onwards.
            </p>
        </div>
    </Authorized>
    <NotAuthorized>
        <div class="enki-card enki-bracket-frame" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">
            <div class="enki-kicker">Access</div>
            <h2 style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0.5rem; font-weight: 300;">
                Sign in to continue
            </h2>
            <p class="enki-dim" style="margin: 0 0 1rem;">
                Enki is gated behind the SDI Identity server. Use the
                <strong>Sign&nbsp;in</strong> button in the top bar.
            </p>
        </div>
    </NotAuthorized>
</AuthorizeView>

@*
    Lore card. Lives on the post-sign-in landing rather than the
    Identity login layout — the login page should be focused on the
    sign-in act itself, the welcome surface is where colour belongs.
    Enki the god is the project's namesake; the text is shaped from
    Sumerian / Akkadian sources, edited for tone.
*@
<div class="enki-card enki-bracket-frame enki-lore-card" style="margin-top: 2rem;">
    <div class="enki-kicker">About the name</div>
    <h2 style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0.25rem; font-weight: 300;">Enki</h2>
    <p class="enki-dim" style="margin: 0 0 1.25rem; font-style: italic;">
        Lord of the Sweet Deep, Cunning of the Gods
    </p>

    <p style="margin: 0 0 1rem;">
        In the elder days, when the heavens were young and the gods
        divided the world between them, Anu took the sky, Enlil
        seized the wind and the storm, and to Enki &mdash; wisest of
        the brothers &mdash; fell the Abz&ucirc;: the great
        freshwater ocean coiled beneath the earth, from which all
        springs and rivers are born.
    </p>
    <p style="margin: 0 0 1rem;">
        There he made his throne. Not upon a mountain of thunder,
        nor a cloud of decree, but in the cool dark beneath the
        world, where wisdom pools and waits to be drawn up.
    </p>
    <p style="margin: 0 0 1rem;">
        The Akkadians named him <em>Ea</em> &mdash; <em>He Whose
        House is Water</em> &mdash; and counted him patron of every
        craft worth practicing: the scribe&rsquo;s reed, the
        smith&rsquo;s hammer, the architect&rsquo;s measure, the
        healer&rsquo;s herb, the magician&rsquo;s word. What Enlil
        ruled by command, Enki shaped by cleverness. Where the elder
        god would have drowned humanity in a flood and called the
        matter settled, it was Enki who whispered through the reed
        wall and warned a mortal to build a boat.
    </p>
    <p style="margin: 0 0 1rem;">
        He is the friend of mortals &mdash; the divine smuggler who
        slipped writing into our hands, taught us to channel rivers
        across the plain, gave us law and loom and lyre when the
        heavens would have kept them locked. He is the god who chose
        craft over command, and wit over wrath, and counted the
        bargain well made.
    </p>
    <p class="enki-dim" style="margin: 0; font-style: italic;">
        Where Enlil thunders, Enki whispers &mdash; and the world
        listens.
    </p>
</div>
